original_title: Brooklyn: New Lots Avenue - Van Siclen Avenue
text:
(1)
569 New Lots Ave., north side, east of Van Siclen Ave., showing the home of the Van Siclen's from about 1730 to 1887. This house was said to have been erected in 1730. It is now, 1929, used as a gasoline station. John Van Siclen during the War of 1812, was employed by the government as a mail carrier. The parsonage of the Dutch reformed church is visible on the left.
About 1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, another view.
About 1929.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

original_title: Brooklyn: Riverdale Avenue - Van Siclen Avenue
text:
Riverdale Ave., at the N.W. corner of Van Siclen Ave., showing the parsonage of a Dutch Reformed Church. It was demolished in March 1929. Now a series of 1-story brick buildings occupy the site.

May 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
